## Security Hardening Quick Reference

**Strict CSP template (mandated; no `'unsafe-inline'`, no `'unsafe-eval'`):**
```
default-src 'self';
script-src 'self' 'nonce-${nonce}' 'strict-dynamic';
style-src 'self' 'nonce-${nonce}';
img-src 'self' blob: data:;
font-src 'self';
connect-src 'self' https://*.workos.com;
frame-src 'self';
object-src 'none';
base-uri 'self';
form-action 'self';
frame-ancestors 'none';
upgrade-insecure-requests;
```
- Nonce generated in `frontend/middleware.ts` per request; root `app/layout.tsx` calls `await headers()` to force dynamic rendering.

**Iframe sandbox:**
- `sandbox="allow-scripts"` only. Forbidden tokens: `allow-same-origin`, `allow-top-navigation`, `allow-forms`, `allow-popups`, `allow-modals`, `allow-pointer-lock`.
- Iframe content via `srcDoc` (origin: `null`), never `src` to external URL.
- CSP `frame-src 'self'` (sandboxed `srcDoc` count as same-origin).

**BFF env policy (F-R9):**
- BFF holds only `WORKOS_CLIENT_ID` (public), `NEXT_PUBLIC_WORKOS_REDIRECT_URI` (public OAuth callback; AuthKit — not `WORKOS_REDIRECT_URI`), `MIDDLEWARE_URL` (public), Next.js framework secrets.
- Never `NEXT_PUBLIC_*` containing `*KEY*`, `*SECRET*`, `*TOKEN*`, `*PRIVATE*`, `*API*`, `*CREDENTIAL*`.
- All credential-bearing calls (Mem0 API key, Langfuse keys, OpenAI/Anthropic keys) flow through `middleware/` only.

**Sealed envelope:**
- `AgentFacts`, `TrustTraceRecord`, `PolicyDecision` typed `Readonly<T>`. Read fields, never mutate.
- Never `{...envelope}`, never `JSON.stringify(JSON.parse(envelope))`. Echo original bytes.

**OWASP additions:**
- `next.config.ts`: `productionBrowserSourceMaps: false`.
- `images.remotePatterns`: explicit allowlist (SSRF prevention).
- JWT in `HttpOnly`, `Secure`, `SameSite=Strict` cookies; never `localStorage` / `sessionStorage`.
- Security headers: HSTS (`max-age=63072000; includeSubDomains; preload`), `X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff`, `X-Frame-Options: DENY`, `Referrer-Policy: strict-origin-when-cross-origin`, `Permissions-Policy: camera=(), microphone=(), geolocation=()`.

## Accessibility Quick Reference (WCAG 2.2 AA)

**Auto-checkable (axe-core 4.5+ / `eslint-plugin-jsx-a11y`):**
- ARIA role validity, required/prohibited attributes.
- HTML structure: lang tag, unique title, correct list/table nesting.
- Form inputs have associated `<label>` (`jsx-a11y/label-has-associated-control`).
- Interactive elements: `<button>`/`<a>` not `<div onClick>` (`jsx-a11y/no-static-element-interactions`).
- WCAG 2.2 `target-size` (axe rule).
- `aria-live` attribute presence and syntactic validity.
- `<iframe sandbox>` token list (custom check).
- Image `alt` attributes.

**Manual / gap territory (record as `gaps`, never as findings):**
- Whether streaming announcement is appropriately timed (not every-token spam).
- Whether focus is preserved during dynamic content updates.
- Whether `alt` text is meaningful (not just present).
- Whether reading order matches visual order.
- Whether color contrast is correct in custom theme variants.
- Screen-reader UX quality.
- WCAG `Focus Appearance`, `Focus Not Obscured` (visual / dynamic-state criteria).

## Performance Quick Reference

**Bundle policy:**
- No fixed initial-load KB target on day 1; measure-first.
- First production build commits `frontend/.bundle-baseline.json`.
- CI fails any route's First Load JS exceeding baseline by `>10%`.
- CopilotKit components not on first paint (Composer, MessageList, generative renderers) imported via `next/dynamic`.
- Pin `@copilotkit/react-core` and `@copilotkit/react-ui` to a version including the issue #3653 `sideEffects` fix (`mermaid`, `shiki`, `streamdown` barrel regression -- ~20MB).

**Streaming hygiene:**
- `cache: 'no-store'` on every user-scoped route.
- Strip `Accept-Encoding` on streaming routes (X6).
- `<Suspense>` boundaries around every async server boundary; named `loading.tsx`.

**Image / code splitting:**
- `next/image` for every content image. `<img>` for content fails review.
- `dynamic(() => import(...))` only for heavy generative-UI components not needed on first paint; reason in JSDoc.

**TTFT target:** `<500ms` p50 cold, `<100ms` p50 warm.

## Testing Pyramid

| Layer | Tool | Required when |
|-------|------|---------------|
| Unit -- pure | Vitest | Any new translator, wire schema, pure helper |
| Unit -- component | Vitest + React Testing Library | Any new component |
| Integration -- adapter | Vitest + MSW | Any new adapter |
| Port conformance | Vitest parametrized over adapters | Any new port OR any new adapter for an existing port |
| Architecture -- TS layering | `ts-morph` walker (`tests/architecture/test_frontend_layering.ts`) | Always runs |
| Architecture -- middleware | `pytest` + `importlib` | Always runs |
| Wire schema drift | Python JSON Schema baseline diff | On any `frontend/lib/wire/` change |
| e2e | Playwright | Critical path per release |
| Accessibility -- static | `eslint-plugin-jsx-a11y` | Always runs in CI |
| Accessibility -- dynamic | `@axe-core/playwright` | On every Playwright route |
| Visual | Storybook stories | Every component under `components/tools/` and `components/generative/` |

**Failure paths first:** rejection tests (401/403/429/5xx/timeout) before happy-path tests for every adapter.

**No live LLM calls in CI.** All adapter tests use MSW mocks or scripted servers.

**`tsc --noEmit` clean.** Type errors block merge. `tsconfig.json` minimum: `"strict": true`, `"noUncheckedIndexedAccess": true`, `"exactOptionalPropertyTypes": true`, `"verbatimModuleSyntax": true`.

## Accepted V3 Deviations (do NOT flag)

The deviations below are **intentional refinements** locked in by `docs/Architectures/FRONTEND_PORT_DEVIATIONS_V3.md` and supplementary Sprint 0/2 decisions. The reviewer MUST treat them as canonical and MUST NOT raise findings against the original spec text.

**D-V3-P1: `AgentRuntimeClient` — split `stream()` into `createRun()` + `streamRun()`; remove `getState()`.**
- Spec (deep-dive §4.1): `stream(req): AsyncIterable<AGUIEvent>; cancel; getState(threadId)`.
- Canonical: `createRun(req): Promise<RunStateView>; streamRun(runId): AsyncIterable<UIRuntimeEvent>; cancel(runId)`.
- Rationale: two-step flow enables `Last-Event-ID` resumption (caller must know the run id before reconnecting), early telemetry attachment, and immediate UI "running" state. `getState(threadId)` moved to `ThreadStore.get(identity, threadId)` (single responsibility).
- Trust boundary preserved: `trace_id` still flows verbatim from backend; browser still never generates one (FE-AP-7 AUTO-REJECT). Transport-level errors with no real `trace_id` use the documented sentinel `"no-trace"`, synthesized in the composition root.
- Yields `UIRuntimeEvent` (post-translation), not raw `AGUIEvent`. The translation lives inside the adapter ring (per `A3`) so component code never observes raw wire events. `UIRuntimeEvent` is itself a `wire/` type so `A4` still holds.

**D-V3-P2: `AuthProvider` — remove `signIn()`; return `IdentityClaim` from `getSession()`.**
- Spec: `getSession(): Promise<Session | null>; getAccessToken; signIn(options?); signOut`.
- Canonical: `getSession(): Promise<IdentityClaim | null>; getAccessToken; signOut`.
- Rationale: WorkOS AuthKit + Next.js 15 are redirect-based — sign-in is `<a href="/api/auth/sign-in">`, an imperative method would be a leaky wrapper around `window.location.assign`. `IdentityClaim` (from `trust-view/identity.ts`) exposes only `{ sub, org_id, roles, email }` — the access token never lands in the structured port surface, eliminating accidental `JSON.stringify(session)` token leaks. JWT storage policy unchanged (HttpOnly + Secure + SameSite=Strict cookie only; FE-AP-18 still AUTO-REJECT).

**D-V3-P3: `ThreadStore` — identity-scoped methods; `rename`/`get` added; `update`/`delete`/`getMessages` removed.**
- Spec: `list; create; update(id, patch); archive(id); delete(id); getMessages(threadId, opts)`.
- Canonical: every method takes `identity: IdentityClaim` first; methods are `create; get; list; rename; archive`.
- Rationale: defense-in-depth (port surface itself enforces ownership; no admin god-mode path); `archive()` is the soft-delete (the spec's `delete()` had identical semantics — collapsed to one method); `rename()` replaces the over-broad `update(id, patch)`; `get(identity, threadId)` returns `null` for both "not found" and "not the owner" (existence-oracle prevention); `getMessages()` deferred to a future expansion when message volume justifies a separate table.

**D-S0-5 (Spike B SKIPPED): self-hosted LangGraph Developer is the v1 path** — already proven by `agent_ui_adapter/server.py`. Reviewer must NOT flag the absence of an LGP Cloud SaaS Plus adapter in `frontend/lib/adapters/runtime/` for v1.

**D-S0-6 (Spike D SKIPPED): Cloud Trace + Cloud Logging is the v1 telemetry path** — Langfuse Cloud Hobby was the V3 default but has been deferred. Reviewer must NOT flag the absence of `LangfuseCloudHobbyAdapter` wiring in `middleware/composition.py` for v1; the `TelemetryExporter` port still exists and is satisfied by a Cloud Logging exporter.

**D-S0-8 (Spike C ACCEPTED with documented latency debt): Mem0 Cloud Hobby retained for v1 despite search p95 = 447.6 ms (vs the 200 ms criterion).** Reviewer must NOT flag the latency miss as a v1 blocker; the alternatives shortlist in `docs/plan/frontend/spike_reports/SPIKE_C_ALTERNATIVES_RESEARCH.md` is the documented re-evaluation trigger.

**Cloudflare Pro WAF entitlement erratum (S2.1.3 → S4.1.1).** Custom WAF rules with action `log` (the basis of S2.1.3's "WAF in count mode for 24h" criterion) require Cloudflare Enterprise. The Pro plan permits custom WAF rules only with enforcing actions (`block`, `challenge`, `js_challenge`, `managed_challenge`, `skip`). Reviewer must NOT flag the absence of a 24h count-mode window. The auto-applied "Cloudflare Free Managed Ruleset" provides the v1 baseline; S4.1.1 goes straight to `block` action and relies on the manual review window already required by the sprint board. Documented in the file header of `infra/dev-tier/cloudflare-edge.tf`.

**Cache Rules Cloudflare API token gap (S2.1.3).** Custom Cache Rules in the `http_request_cache_settings` phase require an additional API-token scope (`Zone:Cache Rules:Edit`) that wasn't in the Sprint 0 token-creation checklist. SSE pass-through is verified by Cloudflare default behaviour (text/event-stream Content-Type bypasses cache + buffering automatically). Reviewer must NOT flag the absence of a custom cache ruleset.

**D-V3-S3.7.1-RouteHandler.** The catch-all WorkOS Route Handler at `frontend/app/api/auth/[...workos]/route.ts` MAY import `handleAuth` directly from `@workos-inc/authkit-nextjs`. Rationale: the catch-all WorkOS route IS the AuthKit composition seam (per `F-R4` / `B6` — Route Handlers are composition adapters); routing through `lib/adapters/auth/workos_server_sdk.ts` would add a no-op wrapper. NOTE: this exception applies ONLY to this single Route Handler file; all OTHER Route Handlers MUST flow through `lib/adapters/`. The reviewer MUST NOT flag `W1` / `FD1.A1` / `FE-AP-13` / `FD8.S3.7.1` SDK leak for this specific file.

**D-V3-S4.2.1-MonitoringDeferred.** `infra/dev-tier/monitoring.tf` is intentionally absent until v1.1. The five 80%-quota alarms (5xx rate, Cloud Run errors, Langfuse, Mem0, Neon CU-hr) remain operational gaps tracked under `OR-MON` in `gaps[]`. The reviewer MUST NOT escalate `FD11.MON` to a finding; it is recorded as `gaps[]` only.

**D-V3-S4.3.2-TTFTColdStart.** `frontend/e2e/smoke.spec.ts` line 341 uses a `2000ms` TTFT threshold rather than the Sprint Board's `500ms` target, with documented rationale "absorb cold starts and network variance". This is a permanent runtime allowance for Cloud Run `min=0` cold-start behaviour. The reviewer MUST NOT flag the threshold as a Sprint Board deviation; it is recorded as accepted operational tuning (cross-references the TTFT target in the Performance Quick Reference of this file).

**D-V3-S2.1.3-CloudflareWAF.** Cloudflare Pro plan does not entitle the `log` action on custom WAF rules (Enterprise-only). The "WAF in count mode for 24h" Sprint Board criterion is permanently superseded by `cloudflare-edge.tf`'s direct-to-`block` ruleset (3 enforce-only rules). Cache Rules are also deferred per the API-token-scope gap above; SSE pass-through is verified by Cloudflare default behaviour for `text/event-stream`. The reviewer MUST NOT flag the absence of a count-mode window or of custom cache rules. Supersedes the original "Cloudflare Pro WAF entitlement erratum" + "Cache Rules Cloudflare API token gap" entries above (kept for backward citation; the substantive guidance is identical).

## Middleware Ring Rules (Python)

Mirror of the M-family enforced by `tests/architecture/test_middleware_layer.py`. Authoritative for FD9 hypotheses.

| ID | Rule | Test |
|----|------|------|
| **M1** | Nothing in `trust/`, `services/`, `components/`, `orchestration/`, `governance/`, `meta/`, or `agent_ui_adapter/` imports from `middleware/`. Dependency arrow is one-way. | `TestM1_BackendDoesNotImportMiddleware::test_no_backend_layer_imports_middleware` |
| **M-F1** | `os.environ["ARCHITECTURE_PROFILE"]` (or `os.getenv(...)`) appears only in `middleware/composition.py`. Module docstrings that mention the literal string are exempt. | `TestF1_SingleProfileSwitch::test_architecture_profile_only_in_composition` |
| **M-F4** | `middleware/` may import from `trust/`, `services/`, `agent_ui_adapter/wire/` — never from `components/`, `orchestration/`, `governance/`, `meta/`. The graph is loaded via `langgraph.json` config string reference, not Python module import. | `TestF4_MiddlewareDependencyDirection::*` (one test per forbidden target) |
| **M-ports** | `middleware/ports/*.py` imports only stdlib + Pydantic + `agent_ui_adapter/wire/` + `trust/`. No SDKs (`jwt`, `mem0`, `mem0ai`, `langfuse`, `workos`), no other middleware sub-packages. | `TestPortPurity::test_ports_have_no_sdk_imports`, `test_ports_do_not_import_adapters` |
| **M-no-cross** | SDKs from `{jwt, mem0, mem0ai, langfuse, workos}` appear ONLY under `middleware/adapters/*` — never in `ports/`, `transport/`, `composition.py`, or `server.py`. Equivalent to `F-R2` / `A1` for the Python ring. | `TestSdkConfinement::test_sdks_only_in_adapters` |
| **M-A2** | An adapter family (`auth | acl | memory | observability`) under `middleware/adapters/` does not import a sibling family. Cross-family wiring goes through the composition root via port instances. | `TestAdapterIsolation::test_no_cross_adapter_imports` |
| **M-server** | `middleware/server.py` does not Python-import `orchestration/`. The graph reference is a string in `langgraph.json` (loaded via the LangGraph Developer config), not a Python import. Specific instance of M-F4. | `TestF4_MiddlewareDependencyDirection::test_middleware_does_not_import_orchestration` |
| **M-composition** | Only `middleware/composition.py` reads `ARCHITECTURE_PROFILE`. Equivalent to `F1` / `C1` / `C5` for the Python ring. | `TestF1_SingleProfileSwitch::test_architecture_profile_only_in_composition` |

The four adapter families today are: `auth/` (WorkOS JWT verifier), `acl/` (tool ACL), `memory/` (Mem0), `observability/` (Langfuse / Cloud Logging). Adding a fifth family requires a merged ADR (mirror of `F2` for the Python ring).

